sentence: Dun & Bradstreet Corp. ( DNB ) reported third-quarter 2014 earnings of $1.85 per share that declined 1.2% from the year-ago quarter but comfortably beat the Zacks Consensus Estimate by 13 cents due to modest revenue growth.
Revenues increased 1.5% on a year-over-year basis to $417.1 million, which missed the Zacks Consensus Estimate of $419 million.
North America core revenues remained flat on a year-over-year basis in the reported quarter.

Risk Management Solutions - North America revenues increased 0.4% year over year to $177.4 million while Sales & Marketing Solutions - North America declined 1% from the year-ago quarter to $127.9 million in the reported quarter.
Revenues from the DNBi subscription plan in North America declined 5%, while non-DNBi subscription plans plunged 6% from the year-ago quarter.
This was offset by an 11% revenue increase in Projects and Other Risk Management Solutions.

D&B's International business segment performed reasonably well in the quarter, with revenues increasing 6.5% year over year, driven by 6.4% revenue growth in Europe & Other International markets and a 6.5% increase in Asia-Pacific.
Risk Management Solutions International revenues increased 7.5% year over year, while Sales & Marketing Solutions International was up 1.6% from the year-ago quarter.
Overall, core revenues from Risk Management Solutions increased 2.7% from the year-ago quarter to $270.5 million in the third quarter.
However, revenues from Sales & Marketing solutions declined 0.6% on a year-over-year basis to $146.6 million.
Total operating costs as a percentage of revenues increased 530 basis points (bps) from the year-ago quarter due to higher selling & administration expense (up 410 bps).
Segment operating margin (prior to corporate expenses) contracted 540 bps to 21.6% in the quarter.
North America operating margin plunged 540 bps while International operating margin expanded 70 bps driven by strong growth in both Asia-Pacific and Europe & Other International markets.
Net income was $67.5 million or $1.85 per share compared with $72.8 million or $1.87 per share in the year-ago quarter.
D&B ended the quarter with $310 million in cash and cash equivalents, up from $285.9 million in the previous quarter.
Total debt was $1.32 billion versus $1.57 billion at the end of the preceding quarter.
During the quarter, D&B repurchased 20 million shares completing its $1 billion discretionary authorization.
The company repurchased approximately $35 million of shares to offset the dilutive effect of shares issued under employee benefit plans.
D&B reiterated its full-year 2014 outlook.
Core revenues are expected to remain almost flat or increase 3% before the effect of foreign exchange.
However, operating income is expected to decline 5% to 9%, before non-core gains and charges.
Earnings per share are expected to decline 1% to 5%, before non-core gains and charges.
Free cash flow is expected to be in the range of $250.0 million to $280.0 million for the full year.
Management expects strategic alliances to be a key driver of revenue growth and long-term margins.

We believe that DNB's high-margin business model, strong international growth potential, international growth opportunities, strategic investments, partnerships, accretive cloud-based acquisitions and aggressive share buyback will drive growth.

We believe that partnerships with the likes of Salesforce.com ( CRM ), Oracle Corp., SugarCRM and FirstRain will help the company to expand its data-as-a-service model, which in turn will drive top-line growth.
We also expect the company to pursue strategic acquisitions that will boost its position in cloud-based offerings.
However, increasing competition from companies such as Equifax Inc. ( EFX ) and Nielsen N.V. ( NLSN ) will continue to hurt revenues and profitability in 2014.
Moreover, higher debt level remains a concern.
